    <!-- ========== WHERE WE ARE ========== -->
    <section id="where-we-are" class="py-20 md:py-28 bg-white">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="fade-in">
          <h2 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-farm-dark mb-10">
            Where we are
          </h2>
          <div class="space-y-6 text-farm-text text-lg leading-relaxed">
            <p>
              In 2024, Drew at Ghost House Farm installed Orisha to run the climate and irrigation in his greenhouse. By the end of that season he had harvested around 2,000 pounds of tomatoes. Roughly 250% of his 2023 yield. Doubled.
            </p>
            <p>
              The moment that reframed everything for us came later, when Drew mentioned that his wife Allison had quit her job to work full-time on the farm. That was the real story. The yield was a means. The life behind the yield was the point.
            </p>
            <p>
              Every farmer we talk to loves what they do, and is quietly crushed by the pressure of it. Too much to do, all at once. So we stopped thinking about yield for its own sake and started thinking about pressure relief through yield. Getting paid enough that you can actually live the life you chose. Greenhouse tomatoes turned out to be the best place to start: highest revenue per bed, by a wide margin. One tomato bed can do the work of twenty or thirty beds of beets or peas.
            </p>
            <p>
              In 2025 we started consulting. Drew was our first remote client. Gordon at Ten Mothers Farm joined in late spring. Within a week of working together, Gordon wrote to us:
            </p>
            <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-farm-green pl-6 italic text-farm-muted">
              Pollination has definitely improved, the tapping works. We've doubled fruit load in 2 weeks.
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              Then heat and bacterial spot erased the win. We hadn't yet learned that he pauses sales in August, so we could have pruned fruit to carry the plants strong into fall. That lesson went into the playbook.
            </p>
            <p>
              Drew's 2025 season started rough. Wilted seedlings, a month behind in May. We fixed pollination in week two and fruit load went up four times in fourteen days. By July 1, he had beaten his entire 2023 season, before the point on the calendar when he had even started harvesting cherry tomatoes in 2023.
            </p>
            <blockquote class="border-l-4 border-farm-green pl-6 italic text-farm-muted">
              I just looked over our 2023 numbers. In the next week or two we will have harvested more pounds of cherry tomatoes than we did in all of 2023. And we will have done so before we even started harvesting cherry tomatoes that year.
              <footer class="text-sm not-italic mt-3 text-farm-muted">Drew, mid-July 2025</footer>
            </blockquote>
            <p>
              Even this season, with a 327 pound single-week record, Drew carried about half the fruit load a plant can actually support. Our best current result is half of what is possible.
            </p>
            <p>
              The program opens in May/June 2026, and stays open after that. The first monthly goal is straightforward: maximize fruit load without exhausting the plant. The playbook is not finished. We are starting with a small group on purpose, so we can listen closely, adapt the coaching format to what we did not foresee, and make sure every farmer gets their questions answered. Going faster would break what we are trying to build.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
